{{draft}}{{infobox religious building | religious_affiliation = | image = Ise Sarutahiko Shrine.jpg | deity = [[Sarutahiko Ōkami]] }} '''[[Sarutahiko Shrine]]''' is a [[shinto shrine]] in [[Ise, Mie]].<ref>https://www.sarutahikojinja.or.jp/english/</ref> located close to [[Ise Grand Shrine]].<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Teeuwen |first1=Mark |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T9rWDQAAQBAJ&dq=Sarutahiko+Shrine&pg=PT393 |title=A Social History of the Ise Shrines: Divine Capital |last2=Breen |first2=John |date=2017-02-09 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |isbn=978-1-4742-7280-3 |language=en}}</ref> It is a [[beppyo shrine]] and a [[Hokora]] in the [[Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|modern system of ranked shinto shrines]].
The priests of the shrine are direct descendants of [[Sarutahiko Ōkami]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Dedicated to Sarutahiko Okami, the Kami of Guidance｜みちひらきの大神 猿田彦神社 |url=https://www.sarutahikojinja.or.jp/english/ |access-date=2023-10-21 |website=www.sarutahikojinja.or.jp}}</ref>
It is linked to [[Tsubaki Grand Shrine]]
==Sarutahiko== {{Short description|Deity in Shinto; leader of the earthly kami}} {{For|the asteroid|10768 Sarutahiko}} {{Shinto}}
'''Sarutahiko Ōkami''' ({{lang-ja|猿田毘古大神, 猿田彦大神}}) is a deity of the [[Religion in Japan|Japanese religion]] of [[Shinto]]; he is the leader of the earthly ''[[kami]]''. [[Norito]] also mentions him with the title {{nihongo3|great bright god, or greatly virtuous god|大明神|Daimyōjin}} instead of {{nihongo3|great god|大神|Ōkami}}. Sarutahiko Ōkami was the head of the [[kunitsukami]]<ref>{{Cite book|last=Picken|first=Stuart D. B.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xlG3F6gSm9UC&dq=Sarutahiko+earth+kami&pg=PA76|title=Historical Dictionary of Shinto|date=2010-12-28|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-7372-8|pages=76|language=en}}</ref> and in the [[Jinnō Shōtōki]] is said to have been the ancestor of [[Otanomikoto]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Otanomikoto • . A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |url=https://historyofjapan.co.uk/wiki/otanomikoto/ |access-date=2023-08-21 |website=. A History . . of Japan . 日本歴史 |language=en-GB}}</ref>
Sarutahiko Ōkami is seen as a symbol of [[Misogi]], strength and guidance, which is why he is the patron of [[Japanese martial arts|martial arts]] such as [[aikido]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Gleason|first=William|title=The Spiritual Foundations of Aikido|year=1995|publisher=Destiny Books|isbn=0-89281-508-6|pages=18|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S4JRDf6C4iMC&pg=PA18}}</ref> He is enshrined at [[Tsubaki Grand Shrine]] in [[Mie Prefecture]], first among the 2000 shrines of Sarutahiko Ōkami, Sarutahiko Jinja in [[Ise, Mie]] and [[Ōasahiko Shrine]] in [[Tokushima Prefecture]]. In the ''[[Nihon Shoki]]'', he is the one who meets [[Ninigi-no-Mikoto]], the grandson of [[Amaterasu]], the Sun goddess, when he descends from [[Takama-ga-hara]].<ref>{{cite web|title=English|url=http://www.sarutahiko-jinjya.net/img/panf_e.pdf|publisher=尾張猿田彦神社|access-date=14 August 2012}}</ref> He is depicted as a towering man with a large beard, jeweled spear, ruddy face, and long nose. At first he is unwilling to let Ninigi pass until persuaded by [[Ame-no-Uzume|Ame-no-Uzume-no-Mikoto]], the kami of dance and the arts, whom he later marries.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shrine History|url=http://www.tsubakishrine.org/history/index.html|publisher=Tsubaki Grand Shrine America|access-date=13 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Roberts|first=Jeremy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdfgjV2kw6oC&q=Ninigi|title=Japanese Mythology A to Z|date=2009|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-2802-3|language=en}}</ref> Even Sarutahiko was regarded as the "god who illuminates the sky and the earth" in Ise, and was worshiped by local believers as the '''sun god''' (personification of sun) before [[Amaterasu]].
He, Ame-no-Uzume and their children subsequently created the ''Sarume no Kimi'' (猿女の君) clan along with an order of female court and religious dancers. It was the origin of [[Kagura]] and [[Noh]]. Other descendants includes the Ujitoko clan from Ise province. According to Kojiki, he went in Ise where a giant clam trapped his hand on Isuzu river at Azaka, thus he drowned. But strangely, Sarutahiko was considered by [[Ueshiba Morihei]] as a kind of god of the cosmic life: the god of Aiki. According to O-Senseï, the practice of [[Aikidō]] was practice of [[Misogi]] purification itself ("and thus, like Sarutahiko standing of ''Ame-no-Ukibashi'', standing between Heaven and Earth, being one with the Universe, and so achieving peace with the world, the next step being World Peace itself"){{cn|date=May 2023}}
[[File:Sarutahiko Ōkami.crop.4.wp.working.print.png|thumb|left|upright|Sarutahiko Ōkami; taken from a late-19th-century Japanese painting.]]
==Etymology== Sarutahiko's name consists of an etymologically obscure element, ''Saruta'', which is traditionally transcribed with [[kanji]] that suggest the meaning "monkey-field" as a sort of double entendre, followed by the [[Classical Japanese language|Classical Japanese]] noun ''hiko'' "a male child of noble blood, a prince."<ref>{{cite book|last=Ashkenazi|first=Michael|title=Handbook of Japanese Mythology|year=2003|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=1-57607-467-6|pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookofjapane0000ashk/page/70 70]|url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofjapane0000ashk|url-access=registration}}</ref> Thus, Sarutahiko Ōkami's embellished name could be roughly translated into English as "Great God, Prince Saruta." Many variant pronunciations of his name exist, including Sarudabiko and Sadahiko. Although it is usually not written, the Japanese genitive case marker, ''-no'', is often suffixed to his name in speech when it is followed immediately by one of his honorific titles, such as ''Ōkami'' or ''Mikoto''.{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}
Anthropologist [[Emiko Ohnuki-Tierney]] lists three factors that identify Sarutahiko as a [[Monkeys in Japanese culture#Religion|monkey deity]]: ''saru'' means "monkey", his features "include red buttocks, which are a prominent characteristic of Japanese macaques", and as macaques gather shellfish at low tide, the ''[[Kojiki]]'' says his hand got caught in a shell while fishing and "a monkey with one hand caught in a shell is a frequent theme of Japanese folktales".<ref>Ohnuki-Tierney, Emiko (1987), ''The Monkey as Mirror: Symbolic Transformations in Japanese History and Ritual'', Princeton University Press, pp. 42-43.</ref>
==Title== Sarutahiko has the distinction of being one of only seven [[kami]] to be honored with the title '''Ōkami''' ({{CJKV|j=大神}}) or "Great Kami"; the other six are [[Izanagi]], [[Izanami-no-Mikoto|Izanami]], [[Michikaeshi]] (also known as Yomido ni sayarimasu ōkami (?) who is the kami of the great rock used by Izanagi to obstruct the way to Yomi, and thus, preventing emergence of evil spirits from the Underworld), [[Sashikuni]], [[Inari Ōkami|Inari]], and [[Amaterasu]]. Sarutahiko and Inari appear to be the only Okami from the ''kunitsukami'', or earthly kami, the others being ''[[Amatsukami]]'' (heavenly deities). Although there is some other Daimyōjin and Daigongen, most of them appeared later in the History of Japanese Religion, such as Hachiman (deification of Empress Jingu, Emperor Ojin and maybe Takeuchi no Sukune, as a successful head of state) or Hindu deities, the meaning of Daimyōjin appear to be a little different from Ōkami, the latter being obviously more ancient. {{Citation needed|date=August 2009}}
==References in music== The name of this deity appears incorrectly spelled as "Sarundasico" in [[Puccini]]'s opera ''[[Madama Butterfly]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=2004 Regular Opera Performance "Madama Butterfly / revised edition"|url=http://www.minna-no-opera.com/eng/opera/2004_btt_gui_e.htm|publisher=NPO Opera del Popolo|access-date=13 August 2012}}</ref>
